# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: american-physiological-society
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:american-physiological-society/american-physiological-society] The **American Physiological Society** is a non-profit professional society for physiologists.
[src:american-physiological-society/american-physiological-society] It has nearly 10,000 members, most of whom hold doctoral degrees in medicine, physiology, or other health professions.
[src:american-physiological-society/american-physiological-society] Its mission is to support research and education in the physiological sciences.
[src:american-physiological-society/american-physiological-society] The society publishes 16 peer-reviewed journals, sponsors scientific conferences, and sponsors awards to further this mission.
[src:american-physiological-society/american-physiological-society] Since it was founded in 1887, APS has had many notable scientists lead the organization, beginning with founder Henry Bowditch and continuing through its current president.
[src:american-physiological-society/american-physiological-society] APS is governed by an elected Board of Directors.
[src:american-physiological-society/american-physiological-society] The Board includes a president, immediate past president and president-elect, each serving a one-year term.
[src:american-physiological-society/american-physiological-society] Management of the affairs of the society is the responsibility of a full-time chief executive officer, who serves as secretary of the board.
[src:american-physiological-society/american-physiological-society] The society maintains a staff and offices in Rockville, Maryland.
[src:american-physiological-society/american-physiological-society] The American Physiological Society was founded in 1887 with 28 members.
[src:american-physiological-society/american-physiological-society] Of them, 21 were graduates of medical schools, but only 12 had studied in institutions with a physiology professor.
[src:american-physiological-society/american-physiological-society] The American Physiological Society was founded at a time when very few physiological laboratories existed in the United States and there were few investigators.
[src:american-physiological-society/american-physiological-society] The newly established society was one of the earliest national disciplinary societies in the sciences, the first society in the biomedical sciences, and likely the first to require its members to publish original research.
[src:american-physiological-society/american-physiological-society] The stated object of the society was to promote the advancement of physiology and to facilitate discourse among American physiologists.
[src:american-physiological-society/american-physiological-society] There was a conscious effort to ensure the representation of all areas within physiology, encompassing topics as diverse as neurology, psychology, ophthalmology, pathology and therapeutics, as well as plant physiology and animal biology.
[src:american-physiological-society/american-physiological-society] The organizational meeting founding the society was held on December 30, 1887, in Curtis' laboratory space at Columbia University and was attended by seventeen people.
[src:american-physiological-society/american-physiological-society] The first regular meeting of the APS followed in September 1888 in Washington, DC, featuring paper presentations and demonstrations.
[src:american-physiological-society/american-physiological-society] In its early days the APS served a young field with relatively few dedicated researchers, so its efforts were oriented toward advancing teaching and research.
[src:american-physiological-society/american-physiological-society] APS members collaborated to author a textbook of physiology and launched a journal, the *American Journal of Physiology*, in 1898.
[src:american-physiological-society/american-physiological-society] As the field of physiology matured, the society expanded in membership.
[src:american-physiological-society/american-physiological-society] The modern APS sponsors many awards, including the Horace W.
[src:american-physiological-society/american-physiological-society] Davenport Distinguished Lecturer, the Walter B.
[src:american-physiological-society/american-physiological-society] Guyton Award, and the Henry Pickering Bowditch Award.
[src:american-physiological-society/american-physiological-society] The American Physiological Society publishes peer-reviewed journals and books as a nonprofit publisher.
[src:american-physiological-society/american-physiological-society] Members can affiliate with one of twelve disciplinary sections composed of members that share a common interest.
[src:american-physiological-society/american-physiological-society] Each member is asked to designate one primary, and two secondary section affiliations.
[src:american-physiological-society/american-physiological-society] Sections have their own internal governance.
[src:american-physiological-society/american-physiological-society] The APS has a variety of membership categories.
[src:american-physiological-society/american-physiological-society] Regular membership is for individuals conducting original research in physiology.
[src:american-physiological-society/american-physiological-society] Affiliate membership is for individuals interested in physiology but without the evidence of scholarly work.
[src:american-physiological-society/american-physiological-society] Graduate Student membership is for any student engaged in physiological work that will culminate in a doctoral degree.
[src:american-physiological-society/american-physiological-society] Undergraduate Student membership is for individuals working toward an undergraduate degree that will eventually lead to work in physiology or a related field.
[src:american-physiological-society/american-physiological-society] The American Physiological Society provides its membership with opportunities to be involved with the society through service on its various committees.
[src:american-physiological-society/american-physiological-society] Currently, the society offers 18 committees for members to get involved in, ranging in topics from science policy to publications.
[src:american-physiological-society/american-physiological-society] In 2023, APS launched its annual meeting, the American Physiology Summit, which convenes thousands of life science researchers and biomedical scientists, educators and students from around the world.
[src:american-physiological-society/american-physiological-society] This meeting features keynotes plenary, award lectures, symposia, oral and poster sessions, and an exhibit of scientific equipment, supplies, and publications.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] Biomedicine also can relate to many other categories in health and biological related fields.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] It has been the dominant system of medicine in the Western world for more than a century.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] Biomedicine is the cornerstone of modern health care and laboratory diagnostics.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] Biomedicine involves the study of (patho-) physiological processes with methods from biology and physiology.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] Approaches range from understanding molecular interactions to the study of the consequences at the in vivo level.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] These processes are studied with the particular point of view of devising new strategies for diagnosis and therapy.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] Depending on the severity of the disease, biomedicine pinpoints a problem within a patient and fixes the problem through medical intervention.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] Medicine focuses on curing diseases rather than improving one's health.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] In social sciences biomedicine is described somewhat differently.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] Through an anthropological lens biomedicine extends beyond the realm of biology and scientific facts; it is a socio-cultural system which collectively represents reality.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] While biomedicine is traditionally thought to have no bias due to the evidence-based practices, Gaines & Davis-Floyd (2004) highlight that biomedicine itself has a cultural basis and this is because biomedicine reflects the norms and values of its creators.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] Molecular biology is the process of synthesis and regulation of a cell's DNA, RNA, and protein.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] Molecular biology consists of different techniques including Polymerase chain reaction, Gel electrophoresis, and macromolecule blotting to manipulate DNA.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] Polymerase chain reaction is done by placing a mixture of the desired DNA, DNA polymerase, primers, and nucleotide bases into a machine.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] The machine heats up and cools down at various temperatures to break the hydrogen bonds binding the DNA and allows the nucleotide bases to be added onto the two DNA templates after it has been separated.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] Gel electrophoresis is a technique used to identify similar DNA between two unknown samples of DNA.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] This process is done by first preparing an agarose gel.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] This jelly-like sheet will have wells for DNA to be poured into.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] An electric current is applied so that the DNA, which is negatively charged due to its phosphate groups is attracted to the positive electrode.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] Different rows of DNA will move at different speeds because some DNA pieces are larger than others.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] Thus if two DNA samples show a similar pattern on the gel electrophoresis, one can tell that these DNA samples match.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] Macromolecule blotting is a process performed after gel electrophoresis.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] An alkaline solution is prepared in a container.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] A sponge is placed into the solution and an agarose gel is placed on top of the sponge.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] Next, nitrocellulose paper is placed on top of the agarose gel and a paper towels are added on top of the nitrocellulose paper to apply pressure.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] The alkaline solution is drawn upwards towards the paper towel.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] During this process, the DNA denatures in the alkaline solution and is carried upwards to the nitrocellulose paper.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] The paper is then placed into a plastic bag and filled with a solution full of the DNA fragments, called the probe, found in the desired sample of DNA.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] The probes anneal to the complementary DNA of the bands already found on the nitrocellulose sample.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] Afterwards, probes are washed off and the only ones present are the ones that have annealed to complementary DNA on the paper.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] Next the paper is stuck onto an x ray film.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] The radioactivity of the probes creates black bands on the film, called an autoradiograph.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] As a result, only similar patterns of DNA to that of the probe are present on the film.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] This allows us the compare similar DNA sequences of multiple DNA samples.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] The overall process results in a precise reading of similarities in both similar and different DNA sample.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] Biochemistry is the science of the chemical processes which takes place within living organisms.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] Living organisms need essential elements to survive, among which are carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, calcium, and phosphorus.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] These elements make up the four macromolecules that living organisms need to survive: carbohydrates, lipids, proteins, and nucleic acids.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] Carbohydrates, made up of carbon, hydrogen, and oxygen, are energy-storing molecules.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] The simplest carbohydrate is glucose (C6H12O6) which is used in cellular respiration to produce ATP, adenosine triphosphate, which supplies cells with energy.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] Proteins are chains of amino acids that function, among other things, to contract skeletal muscle, as catalysts, as transport molecules, and as storage molecules.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] Protein catalysts can facilitate biochemical processes by lowering the activation energy of a reaction.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] Hemoglobins are also proteins, carrying oxygen to an organism's cells.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] Lipids, also known as fats, are small molecules derived from biochemical subunits from either the ketoacyl or isoprene groups.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] Creating eight distinct categories: fatty acids, glycerolipids, glycerophospholipids, sphingolipids, saccharolipids, and polyketides (derived from condensation of ketoacyl subunits); and sterol lipids and prenol lipids (derived from condensation of isoprene subunits).
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] Their primary purpose is to store energy over the long term.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] Due to their unique structure, lipids provide more than twice the amount of energy that carbohydrates do.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] Moreover, lipids can be used in hormone production to maintain a healthy hormonal balance and provide structure to cell membranes.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] Nucleic acids are a key component of DNA, the main genetic information-storing substance, found oftentimes in the cell nucleus, and controls the metabolic processes of the cell.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] DNA consists of two complementary antiparallel strands consisting of varying patterns of nucleotides.
[src:american-physiological-society/biomedical] RNA is a single strand of DNA, which is transcribed from DNA and used for DNA translation, which is the process for making proteins out of RNA sequences.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] There are five types of blood vessels: the arteries, which carry the blood away from the heart; the arterioles; the capillaries, where the exchange of water and chemicals between the blood and tissues occurs; the venules; and the veins, which carry blood from the capillaries back towards the heart.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] The word, *vascular*, is derived from the Latin *vas*, meaning *vessel*, and is used in reference to blood vessels.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] The arteries and veins have three layers.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] Capillaries consist of a single layer of endothelial cells with a supporting subendothelium consisting of a basement membrane and connective tissue.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] When blood vessels connect to form a region of diffuse vascular supply, it is called an anastomosis.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] Anastomoses provide alternative routes for blood to flow through in case of blockages.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] Veins can have valves that prevent the backflow of the blood that was being pumped against gravity by the surrounding muscles.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] In humans, arteries do not have valves except for the two 'arteries' that originate from the heart's ventricles.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] Early estimates by Danish physiologist August Krogh suggested that the total length of capillaries in human muscles could reach approximately 100,000 kilometres (62,000 mi) (assuming a high muscle mass human body, like that of a bodybuilder).
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] However, later studies suggest a more conservative figure of 9,000–19,000 kilometres (5,600–11,800 mi) taking into account updated capillary density and average muscle mass in adults.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] They are roughly grouped as "arterial" and "venous", determined by whether the blood in it is flowing *away from* (arterial) or *toward* (venous) the heart.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] The term "arterial blood" is nevertheless used to indicate blood high in oxygen, although the pulmonary artery carries "venous blood" and blood flowing in the pulmonary vein is rich in oxygen.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] This is because they are carrying the blood to and from the lungs, respectively, to be oxygenated.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] Blood vessels function to transport blood to an animal's body tissues.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] In general, arteries and arterioles transport oxygenated blood from the lungs to the body and its organs, and veins and venules transport deoxygenated blood from the body to the lungs.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] Blood vessels also circulate blood throughout the circulatory system.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] Oxygen (bound to hemoglobin in red blood cells) is the most critical nutrient carried by the blood.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] In all arteries apart from the pulmonary artery, hemoglobin is highly saturated (95–100%) with oxygen.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] In all veins, apart from the pulmonary vein, the saturation of hemoglobin is about 75%.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] (The values are reversed in the pulmonary circulation.) In addition to carrying oxygen, blood also carries hormones, and nutrients to the cells of a body and removes waste products.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] Blood vessels do not actively engage in the transport of blood (they have no appreciable peristalsis).
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] Blood is propelled through arteries and arterioles through pressure generated by the heartbeat.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] Blood vessels also transport red blood cells.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] Hematocrit tests can be performed to calculate the proportion of red blood cells in the blood.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] Higher proportions result in conditions such as dehydration or heart disease, while lower proportions could lead to anemia and long-term blood loss.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] Permeability of the endothelium is pivotal in the release of nutrients to the tissue.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] It is also increased in inflammation in response to histamine, prostaglandins and interleukins, which leads to most of the symptoms of inflammation (swelling, redness, warmth and pain).
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] Arteries—and veins to a degree—can regulate their inner diameter by contraction of the muscular layer.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] This changes the blood flow to downstream organs and is determined by the autonomic nervous system.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] Vasodilation and vasoconstriction are also used antagonistically as methods of thermoregulation.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] The size of blood vessels is different for each of them.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] It ranges from a diameter of about 30–25 millimeters for the aorta to only about 5 micrometers (0,005 mm) for the capillaries.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] Vasoconstriction is the constriction of blood vessels (narrowing, becoming smaller in cross-sectional area) by contracting the vascular smooth muscle in the vessel walls.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] It is regulated by vasoconstrictors (agents that cause vasoconstriction).
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] These can include paracrine factors (e.g., prostaglandins), a number of hormones (e.g., vasopressin and angiotensin) and neurotransmitters (e.g., epinephrine) from the nervous system.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] Vasodilation is a similar process mediated by antagonistically acting mediators.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] The most prominent vasodilator is nitric oxide (termed endothelium-derived relaxing factor for this reason).
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] The circulatory system uses the channel of blood vessels to deliver blood to all parts of the body.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] This is a result of the left and right sides of the heart working together to allow blood to flow continuously to the lungs and other parts of the body.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] Oxygen-poor blood enters the right side of the heart through two large veins.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] Oxygen-rich blood from the lungs enters through the pulmonary veins on the left side of the heart into the aorta and then reaches the rest of the body.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] The capillaries are responsible for allowing the blood to receive oxygen through tiny air sacs in the lungs.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] This is also the site where carbon dioxide exits the blood.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] This all occurs in the lungs where blood is oxygenated.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] The blood pressure in blood vessels is traditionally expressed in millimetres of mercury (1 mmHg = 133 Pa).
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] In the arterial system, this is usually around 120 mmHg systolic (high pressure wave due to contraction of the heart) and 80 mmHg diastolic (low pressure wave).
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] In contrast, pressures in the venous system are constant and rarely exceed 10 mmHg.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] Vascular resistance occurs when the vessels away from the heart oppose the flow of blood.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] Resistance is an accumulation of three different factors: blood viscosity, blood vessel length and vessel radius.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] Blood viscosity is the thickness of the blood and its resistance to flow as a result of the different components of the blood.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] Blood is 92% water by weight and the rest of blood is composed of protein, nutrients, electrolytes, wastes, and dissolved gases.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] Depending on the health of an individual, the blood viscosity can vary (i.e., anemia causing relatively lower concentrations of protein, high blood pressure an increase in dissolved salts or lipids, etc.).
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] Vessel length is the total length of the vessel measured as the distance away from the heart.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] As the total length of the vessel increases, the total resistance as a result of friction will increase.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] Vessel radius also affects the total resistance as a result of contact with the vessel wall.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] As the radius of the wall gets smaller, the proportion of the blood making contact with the wall will increase.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] The greater amount of contact with the wall will increase the total resistance against the blood flow.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] Blood vessels play a role in virtually every medical condition.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] Cancer, for example, cannot progress unless the tumor causes angiogenesis (formation of new blood vessels) to supply its metabolic demand.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] Atherosclerosis represents around 85% of all deaths from cardiovascular diseases due to plaque formation.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] Coronary artery disease that often follows after atherosclerosis can cause heart attacks or cardiac arrest, resulting in 919,032 deaths in the United States in 2023.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] In 2019, around 17.9 million people died from cardiovascular diseases worldwide.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] Of these deaths, around 85% of them were due to heart attack and stroke.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] Blood vessel inflammation may lead to hemorrhage due to mechanical damage in the vessel endothelium.
[src:american-physiological-society/blood-vessel] Anti-inflammatory treatment may require multiple therapies to control blood lipids, inflammatory cytokines, and blood clots.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] In vertebrates, the **circulatory system** is a system of organs that includes the heart, blood vessels, and blood which is circulated throughout the body.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] It includes the cardiovascular system, or vascular system, that consists of the heart and blood vessels (from Greek *kardia* meaning *heart*, and Latin *vascula* meaning *vessels*).
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The circulatory system has two divisions, a systemic circulation or circuit, and a pulmonary circulation or circuit.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Some sources use the terms *cardiovascular system* and *vascular system* interchangeably with *circulatory system*.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The network of blood vessels are the great vessels of the heart including large elastic arteries, and large veins; other arteries, smaller arterioles, capillaries that join with venules (small veins), and other veins.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The circulatory system is closed in vertebrates, which means that the blood never leaves the network of blood vessels.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Many invertebrates such as arthropods have an open circulatory system with a heart that pumps a hemolymph which returns via the body cavity rather than via blood vessels.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Diploblasts such as sponges and comb jellies lack a circulatory system.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Blood is a fluid consisting of plasma, red blood cells, white blood cells, and platelets; it is circulated around the body carrying oxygen and nutrients to the tissues and collecting and disposing of waste materials.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Circulated nutrients include proteins and minerals and other components include hemoglobin, hormones, and gases such as oxygen and carbon dioxide.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] These substances provide nourishment, help the immune system to fight diseases, and help maintain homeostasis by stabilizing temperature and natural pH.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] In vertebrates, the lymphatic system is complementary to the circulatory system.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The lymphatic system carries excess plasma (filtered from the circulatory system capillaries as interstitial fluid between cells) away from the body tissues via accessory routes that return excess fluid back to blood circulation as lymph.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The lymphatic system is a subsystem that is essential for the functioning of the blood circulatory system; without it the blood would become depleted of fluid.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The lymphatic system also works with the immune system.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The circulation of lymph takes much longer than that of blood and, unlike the closed (blood) circulatory system, the lymphatic system is an open system.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Some sources describe it as a *secondary circulatory system*.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The circulatory system can be affected by many cardiovascular diseases.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Cardiologists are medical professionals which specialise in the heart, and cardiothoracic surgeons specialise in operating on the heart and its surrounding areas.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Vascular surgeons focus on disorders of the blood vessels, and lymphatic vessels.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The circulatory system includes the heart, blood vessels, and blood.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The cardiovascular system in all vertebrates, consists of the heart and blood vessels.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The circulatory system is further divided into two major circuits – a pulmonary circulation, and a systemic circulation.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The pulmonary circulation is a circuit loop from the right heart taking deoxygenated blood to the lungs where it is oxygenated and returned to the left heart.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The systemic circulation is a circuit loop that delivers oxygenated blood from the left heart to the rest of the body, and returns deoxygenated blood back to the right heart via large veins known as the venae cavae.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The systemic circulation can also be defined as two parts – a *macrocirculation* and a *microcirculation*.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] An average adult contains five to six quarts (roughly 4.7 to 5.7 liters) of blood, accounting for approximately 7% of their total body weight.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Blood consists of plasma, red blood cells, white blood cells, and platelets.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The digestive system also works with the circulatory system to provide the nutrients the system needs to keep the heart pumping.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Further circulatory routes are associated, such as the coronary circulation to the heart itself, the cerebral circulation to the brain, renal circulation to the kidneys, and bronchial circulation to the bronchi in the lungs.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The human circulatory system is closed, meaning that the blood is contained within the vascular network.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Nutrients travel through tiny blood vessels of the microcirculation to reach organs.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The lymphatic system is an essential subsystem of the circulatory system consisting of a network of lymphatic vessels, lymph nodes, organs, tissues and circulating lymph.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] A major function is to carry the lymph, draining and returning interstitial fluid into the lymphatic ducts back to the heart for return to the circulatory system.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Another major function is working together with the immune system to provide defense against pathogens.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The heart pumps blood to all parts of the body.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] In the human heart there is one atrium and one ventricle for each circulation, and with both a systemic and a pulmonary circulation there are four chambers in total: left atrium, left ventricle, right atrium and right ventricle.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Gas exchange occurs in the lungs, whereby CO2 is released from the blood, and oxygen is absorbed.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The pulmonary vein returns the now oxygen-rich blood to the left atrium.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] A separate circuit from the systemic circulation, the bronchial circulation supplies blood to the tissue of the larger airways of the lung.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The systemic circulation is a circuit loop that delivers oxygenated blood from the left heart to the rest of the body through the aorta.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Deoxygenated blood is returned in the systemic circulation to the right heart via two large veins, the inferior vena cava and superior vena cava, where it is pumped from the right atrium into the pulmonary circulation for oxygenation.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The systemic circulation can also be defined as having two parts – a macrocirculation and a microcirculation.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The blood vessels of the circulatory system are the arteries, veins, and capillaries.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The large arteries and veins that take blood to, and away from the heart are known as the great vessels.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Oxygenated blood enters the systemic circulation when leaving the left ventricle, via the aortic semilunar valve.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The first part of the systemic circulation is the aorta, a massive and thick-walled artery.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The aorta arches and gives branches supplying the upper part of the body after passing through the aortic opening of the diaphragm at the level of thoracic ten vertebra, it enters the abdomen.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Later, it descends down and supplies branches to abdomen, pelvis, perineum and the lower limbs.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] This elasticity helps to maintain the blood pressure throughout the body.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] When the aorta receives almost five litres of blood from the heart, it recoils and is responsible for pulsating blood pressure.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] As the aorta branches into smaller arteries, their elasticity goes on decreasing and their compliance goes on increasing.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Arteries branch into small passages called arterioles and then into the capillaries.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The capillaries merge to bring blood into the venous system.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The total length of muscle capillaries in a 70 kg human is estimated to be between 9,000 and 19,000 km.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Capillaries merge into venules, which merge into veins.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The venous system feeds into the two major veins: the superior vena cava – which mainly drains tissues above the heart – and the inferior vena cava – which mainly drains tissues below the heart.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] These two large veins empty into the right atrium of the heart.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The general rule is that arteries from the heart branch out into capillaries, which collect into veins leading back to the heart.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Portal veins are a slight exception to this.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The heart itself is supplied with oxygen and nutrients through a small "loop" of the systemic circulation and derives very little from the blood contained within the four chambers.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The coronary circulation system provides a blood supply to the heart muscle itself.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The coronary circulation begins near the origin of the aorta by two coronary arteries: the right coronary artery and the left coronary artery.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] After nourishing the heart muscle, blood returns through the coronary veins into the coronary sinus and from this one into the right atrium.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Backflow of blood through its opening during atrial systole is prevented by the Thebesian valve.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The smallest cardiac veins drain directly into the heart chambers.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The brain has a dual blood supply, an *anterior* and a *posterior circulation* from arteries at its front and back.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The anterior circulation arises from the internal carotid arteries to supply the front of the brain.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The posterior circulation arises from the vertebral arteries, to supply the back of the brain and brainstem.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The circulation from the front and the back join (anastomise) at the circle of Willis.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The neurovascular unit, composed of various cells and vasculature channels within the brain, regulates the flow of blood to activated neurons in order to satisfy their high energy demands.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The renal circulation is the blood supply to the kidneys, contains many specialized blood vessels and receives around 20% of the cardiac output.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] It branches from the abdominal aorta and returns blood to the ascending inferior vena cava.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The development of the circulatory system starts with vasculogenesis in the embryo.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The human arterial and venous systems develop from different areas in the embryo.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The arterial system develops mainly from the aortic arches, six pairs of arches that develop on the upper part of the embryo.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The venous system arises from three bilateral veins during weeks 4 – 8 of embryogenesis.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Fetal circulation begins within the 8th week of development.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Fetal circulation does not include the lungs, which are bypassed via the truncus arteriosus.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Before birth the fetus obtains oxygen (and nutrients) from the mother through the placenta and the umbilical cord.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The human arterial system originates from the aortic arches and from the dorsal aortae starting from week 4 of embryonic life.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The first and second aortic arches regress and form only the maxillary arteries and stapedial arteries respectively.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The arterial system itself arises from aortic arches 3, 4 and 6 (aortic arch 5 completely regresses).
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The dorsal aortae, present on the dorsal side of the embryo, are initially present on both sides of the embryo.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] They later fuse to form the basis for the aorta itself.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Approximately thirty smaller arteries branch from this at the back and sides.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] These branches form the intercostal arteries, arteries of the arms and legs, lumbar arteries and the lateral sacral arteries.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Branches to the sides of the aorta will form the definitive renal, suprarenal and gonadal arteries.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Finally, branches at the front of the aorta consist of the vitelline arteries and umbilical arteries.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The vitelline arteries form the celiac, superior and inferior mesenteric arteries of the gastrointestinal tract.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] After birth, the umbilical arteries will form the internal iliac arteries.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The human venous system develops mainly from the vitelline veins, the umbilical veins and the cardinal veins, all of which empty into the sinus venosus.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] About 98.5% of the oxygen in a sample of arterial blood in a healthy human, breathing air at sea-level pressure, is chemically combined with hemoglobin molecules.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] About 1.5% is physically dissolved in the other blood liquids and not connected to hemoglobin.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The hemoglobin molecule is the primary transporter of oxygen in vertebrates.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Many diseases affect the circulatory system.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] These include a number of cardiovascular diseases, affecting the heart and blood vessels; hematologic diseases that affect the blood, such as anemia, and lymphatic diseases affecting the lymphatic system.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Vascular surgeons focus on the blood vessels.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Diseases affecting the cardiovascular system are called *cardiovascular disease*.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Many of these diseases are called "lifestyle diseases" because they develop over time and are related to a person's exercise habits, diet, whether they smoke, and other lifestyle choices a person makes.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Atherosclerosis is the precursor to many of these diseases.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] It is where small atheromatous plaques build up in the walls of medium and large arteries.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] This may eventually grow or rupture to occlude the arteries.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] It is also a risk factor for acute coronary syndromes, which are diseases that are characterised by a sudden deficit of oxygenated blood to the heart tissue.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Atherosclerosis is also associated with problems such as aneurysm formation or splitting ("dissection") of arteries.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Another major cardiovascular disease involves the creation of a clot, called a "thrombus".
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] These can originate in veins or arteries.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Deep venous thrombosis, which mostly occurs in the legs, is one cause of clots in the veins of the legs, particularly when a person has been stationary for a long time.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] These clots may embolise, meaning travel to another location in the body.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The results of this may include pulmonary embolus, transient ischaemic attacks, or stroke.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Cardiovascular diseases may also be congenital in nature, such as heart defects or persistent fetal circulation, where the circulatory changes that are supposed to happen after birth do not.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Not all congenital changes to the circulatory system are associated with diseases, a large number are anatomical variations.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The function and health of the circulatory system and its parts are measured in a variety of manual and automated ways.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] An electrocardiogram can also be used to evaluate the way in which electricity is conducted through the heart.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Other more invasive means can also be used.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] A cannula or catheter inserted into an artery may be used to measure pulse pressure or pulmonary wedge pressures.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Angiography, which involves injecting a dye into an artery to visualise an arterial tree, can be used in the heart (coronary angiography) or brain.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] At the same time as the arteries are visualised, blockages or narrowings may be fixed through the insertion of stents, and active bleeds may be managed by the insertion of coils.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] An MRI may be used to image arteries, called an MRI angiogram.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] For evaluation of the blood supply to the lungs a CT pulmonary angiogram may be used.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Vascular ultrasonography may be used to investigate vascular diseases affecting the venous system and the arterial system including the diagnosis of stenosis, thrombosis or venous insufficiency.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] An intravascular ultrasound using a catheter is also an option.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Surgical treatment of disorders of the circulatory system may be carried out by cardiothoracic surgeons who specialize in diseases of the heart and thoracic organs or vascular surgeons who specialize in disorders of blood vessels.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Many procedures conducted on the heart or great vessels rely on the use of cardiopulmonary bypass, a machine that oxygenates and circulates the patient's blood, allowing the surgeon to operate on the patient's heart and/or vessels.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Cardiovascular procedures are more likely to be performed in an inpatient setting than in an ambulatory care setting; in the United States, only 28% of cardiovascular surgeries were performed in the ambulatory care setting.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] While humans, as well as other vertebrates, have a closed blood circulatory system (meaning that the blood never leaves the network of arteries, veins and capillaries), some invertebrate groups have an open circulatory system containing a heart but limited blood vessels.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The most primitive, diploblastic animal phyla lack circulatory systems.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] An additional transport system, the lymphatic system, which is only found in animals with a closed blood circulation, is an open system providing an accessory route for excess interstitial fluid to be returned to the blood.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The blood vascular system first appeared probably in an ancestor of the triploblasts over 600 million years ago, overcoming the time-distance constraints of diffusion, while endothelium evolved in an ancestral vertebrate some 540–510 million years ago.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Muscular movements by the animal during locomotion can facilitate hemolymph movement, but diverting flow from one area to another is limited.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] When the heart relaxes, blood is drawn back toward the heart through open-ended pores (ostia).
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Hemolymph fills all of the interior hemocoel of the body and surrounds all cells.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Hemolymph is composed of water, inorganic salts (mostly sodium, chloride, potassium, magnesium, and calcium), and organic compounds (mostly carbohydrates, proteins, and lipids).
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The primary oxygen transporter molecule is hemocyanin.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] There are free-floating cells, the hemocytes, within the hemolymph.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] They play a role in the arthropod immune system.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The circulatory systems of all vertebrates, as well as of annelids (for example, earthworms) and cephalopods (squids, octopuses and relatives) always keep their circulating blood enclosed within heart chambers or blood vessels and are classified as *closed*, just as in humans.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Still, the systems of fish, amphibians, reptiles, and birds show various stages of the evolution of the circulatory system.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Closed systems permit blood to be directed to the organs that require it.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] In fish, the system has only one circuit, with the blood being pumped through the capillaries of the gills and on to the capillaries of the body tissues.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] This is known as *single cycle* circulation.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The heart of fish is, therefore, only a single pump (consisting of two chambers).
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] In amphibians and most reptiles, a double circulatory system is used, but the heart is not always completely separated into two pumps.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Amphibians have a three-chambered heart.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] In reptiles, the ventricular septum of the heart is incomplete and the pulmonary artery is equipped with a sphincter muscle.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] This allows a second possible route of blood flow.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Instead of blood flowing through the pulmonary artery to the lungs, the sphincter may be contracted to divert this blood flow through the incomplete ventricular septum into the left ventricle and out through the aorta.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] This means the blood flows from the capillaries to the heart and back to the capillaries instead of to the lungs.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] This process is useful to ectothermic (cold-blooded) animals in the regulation of their body temperature.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Mammals, birds and crocodilians show complete separation of the heart into two pumps, for a total of four heart chambers; it is thought that the four-chambered heart of birds and crocodilians evolved independently from that of mammals.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Double circulatory systems permit blood to be repressurized after returning from the lungs, speeding up delivery of oxygen to tissues.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Circulatory systems are absent in some animals, including flatworms.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Their body cavity has no lining or enclosed fluid.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Instead, a muscular pharynx leads to an extensively branched digestive system that facilitates direct diffusion of nutrients to all cells.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The flatworm's dorso-ventrally flattened body shape also restricts the distance of any cell from the digestive system or the exterior of the organism.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Oxygen can diffuse from the surrounding water into the cells, and carbon dioxide can diffuse out.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Consequently, every cell is able to obtain nutrients, water and oxygen without the need of a transport system.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Some animals, such as jellyfish, have more extensive branching from their gastrovascular cavity (which functions as both a place of digestion and a form of circulation), this branching allows for bodily fluids to reach the outer layers, since the digestion begins in the inner layers.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The earliest known writings on the circulatory system are found in the Ebers Papyrus (16th century BCE), an ancient Egyptian medical papyrus containing over 700 prescriptions and remedies, both physical and spiritual.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] In the papyrus, it acknowledges the connection of the heart to the arteries.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The Egyptians thought air came in through the mouth and into the lungs and heart.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] From the heart, the air travelled to every member through the arteries.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Although this concept of the circulatory system is only partially correct, it represents one of the earliest accounts of scientific thought.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] In the 6th century BCE, the knowledge of circulation of vital fluids through the body was known to the Ayurvedic physician Sushruta in ancient India.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] He also seems to have possessed knowledge of the arteries, described as 'channels' by Dwivedi & Dwivedi (2007).
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The valves of the heart were discovered by a physician of the Hippocratic school around the early 3rd century BC.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] However, their function was not properly understood then.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Because blood pools in the veins after death, arteries look empty.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Ancient anatomists assumed they were filled with air and that they were for the transport of air.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The Greek physician, Herophilus, distinguished veins from arteries but thought that the pulse was a property of arteries themselves.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Greek anatomist Erasistratus observed that arteries that were cut during life bleed.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] He ascribed the fact to the phenomenon that air escaping from an artery is replaced with blood that enters between veins and arteries by very small vessels.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Thus he apparently postulated capillaries but with reversed flow of blood.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] In 2nd-century AD Rome, the Greek physician Galen knew that blood vessels carried blood and identified venous (dark red) and arterial (brighter and thinner) blood, each with distinct and separate functions.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Growth and energy were derived from venous blood created in the liver from chyle, while arterial blood gave vitality by containing pneuma (air) and originated in the heart.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Blood flowed from both creating organs to all parts of the body where it was consumed and there was no return of blood to the heart or liver.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] The heart did not pump blood around, the heart's motion sucked blood in during diastole and the blood moved by the pulsation of the arteries themselves.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Galen believed that the arterial blood was created by venous blood passing from the left ventricle to the right by passing through 'pores' in the interventricular septum, air passed from the lungs via the pulmonary artery to the left side of the heart.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] As the arterial blood was created 'sooty' vapors were created and passed to the lungs also via the pulmonary artery to be exhaled.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] While also refining Galen's erroneous theory of the pulse, Avicenna provided the first correct explanation of pulsation: "Every beat of the pulse comprises two movements and two pauses.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] In 1242, the Arabian physician, Ibn al-Nafis described the process of pulmonary circulation in greater, more accurate detail than his predecessors, though he believed, as they did, in the notion of vital spirit (pneuma), which he believed was formed in the left ventricle.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] In addition, Ibn al-Nafis had an insight into what later became a larger theory of the capillary circulation.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] He stated that "there must be small communications or pores (*manafidh* in Arabic) between the pulmonary artery and vein," a prediction that preceded the discovery of the capillary system by more than 400 years.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Ibn al-Nafis' theory was confined to blood transit in the lungs and did not extend to the entire body.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Michael Servetus was the first European to describe the function of pulmonary circulation, although his achievement was not widely recognized at the time, for a few reasons.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] He firstly described it in the "Manuscript of Paris" (near 1546), but this work was never published.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] And later he published this description, but in a theological treatise, *Christianismi Restitutio*, not in a book on medicine.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Only three copies of the book survived but these remained hidden for decades, the rest were burned shortly after its publication in 1553 because of persecution of Servetus by religious authorities.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] A better known discovery of pulmonary circulation was by Vesalius's successor at Padua, Realdo Colombo, in 1559.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] Most importantly, he argued that the beat of the heart produced a continuous circulation of blood through minute connections at the extremities of the body.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] This is a conceptual leap that was quite different from Ibn al-Nafis' refinement of the anatomy and bloodflow in the heart and lungs." This work, with its essentially correct exposition, slowly convinced the medical world.
[src:american-physiological-society/cardiovascular] However, Harvey did not identify the capillary system connecting arteries and veins; this was discovered by Marcello Malpighi in 1661.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] There are two types of cells: prokaryotes and eukaryotes.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] Prokaryotes were the first of the two to develop and do not have a self-contained nucleus.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] Their mechanisms are simpler than later-evolved eukaryotes, which contain a nucleus that envelops the cell's DNA and some organelles.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] Prokaryotes have DNA located in an area called the nucleoid, which is not separated from other parts of the cell by a membrane.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] There are two domains of prokaryotes: bacteria and archaea.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] Prokaryotes have fewer organelles than eukaryotes.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] Both have plasma membranes and ribosomes (structures that synthesize proteins and float free in cytoplasm).
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] Two unique characteristics of prokaryotes are fimbriae (finger-like projections on the surface of a cell) and flagella (threadlike structures that aid movement).
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] Eukaryotes have a nucleus where DNA is contained.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] They are usually larger than prokaryotes and contain many more organelles.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] The nucleus, the feature of a eukaryote that distinguishes it from a prokaryote, contains a nuclear envelope, nucleolus and chromatin.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] In cytoplasm, endoplasmic reticulum (ER) synthesizes membranes and performs other metabolic activities.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] There are two types, rough ER (containing ribosomes) and smooth ER (lacking ribosomes).
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] The Golgi apparatus consists of multiple membranous sacs, responsible for manufacturing and shipping out materials such as proteins.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] Lysosomes are structures that use enzymes to break down substances through phagocytosis, a process that comprises endocytosis and exocytosis.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] In the mitochondria, metabolic processes such as cellular respiration occur.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] The cytoskeleton is made of fibers that support the structure of the cell and help the cell move.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] There are different ways through which cells can transport substances across the cell membrane.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] The two main pathways are passive transport and active transport.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] Passive transport is more direct and does not require the use of the cell's energy.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] It relies on an area that maintains a high-to-low concentration gradient.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] Active transport uses adenosine triphosphate (ATP) to transport a substance that moves against its concentration gradient.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] The pathway for proteins to move in cells starts at the ER.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] Lipids and proteins are synthesized in the ER, and carbohydrates are added to make glycoproteins.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] Glycoproteins undergo further synthesis in the Golgi apparatus, becoming glycolipids.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] Both glycoproteins and glycolipids are transported into vesicles to the plasma membrane.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] The cell releases secretory proteins known as exocytosis.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] Ions travel across cell membranes through channels, pumps or transporters.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] In channels, they move down an electrochemical gradient to produce electrical signals.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] Pumps maintain electrochemical gradients.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] It moves 3 sodium ions out of a cell and 2 potassium ions into a cell.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] The process converts one ATP molecule to adenosine diphosphate (ADP) and Phosphate.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] In a transporter, ions use more than one gradient to produce electrical signals.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] Endocytosis is a form of active transport where a cell takes in molecules, using the plasma membrane, and packages them into vesicles.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] In phagocytosis, a cell surrounds particles including food particles through an extension of the pseudopods, which are located on the plasma membrane.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] The pseudopods then package the particles in a food vacuole.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] The lysosome, which contains hydrolytic enzymes, then fuses with the food vacuole.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] Hydrolytic enzymes, also known as digestive enzymes, then digest the particles within the food vacuole.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] In pinocytosis, a cell takes in ("gulps") extracellular fluid into vesicles, which are formed when plasma membrane surrounds the fluid.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] The cell can take in any molecule or solute through this process.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] Receptor-mediated endocytosis is a form of pinocytosis where a cell takes in specific molecules or solutes.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] Proteins with receptor sites are located on the plasma membrane, binding to specific solutes.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] The receptor proteins that are attached to the specific solutes go inside coated pits, forming a vesicle.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] The vesicles then surround the receptors that are attached to the specific solutes, releasing their molecules.
[src:american-physiological-society/cell-physiology] Receptor proteins are recycled back to the plasma membrane by the same vesicle.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The **central nervous system** (**CNS**) is the part of the nervous system consisting primarily of the brain, and the spinal cord.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The retina is also technically part of the CNS.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The CNS is named so because the brain integrates the received information and coordinates and influences the activity of all parts of the bodies of bilaterally symmetric and triploblastic animals—that is, all multicellular animals except sponges and diploblasts.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] It is a structure composed of nervous tissue positioned along the rostral (nose end) to caudal (tail end) axis of the body and may have an enlarged section at the rostral end which is a brain.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Only arthropods, cephalopods and vertebrates have a true brain, though precursor structures exist in onychophorans, gastropods and lancelets.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The rest of this article exclusively discusses the vertebrate central nervous system, which is radically distinct from all other animals.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] In vertebrates, the brain and spinal cord are both enclosed in the meninges.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The meninges provide a barrier to chemicals dissolved in the blood, protecting the brain from most neurotoxins commonly found in food.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Within the meninges the brain and spinal cord are bathed in cerebral spinal fluid which replaces the body fluid found outside the cells of all bilateral animals.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] In vertebrates, the CNS is contained within the dorsal body cavity, while the brain is housed in the cranial cavity within the skull.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The spinal cord is housed in the spinal canal within the vertebrae.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Within the CNS, the interneuronal space is filled with a large amount of supporting non-nervous cells called neuroglia or glia from the Greek for "glue".
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] In vertebrates, the CNS also includes the retina, and the optic nerve (cranial nerve II), as well as the olfactory nerves and olfactory epithelium.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] As parts of the CNS, they connect directly to brain neurons without intermediate ganglia.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The olfactory epithelium is the only central nervous tissue outside the meninges in direct contact with the environment, which opens up a pathway for therapeutic agents which cannot otherwise cross the meninges barrier.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The CNS consists of two major structures: the brain and spinal cord.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The brain is encased in the skull, and protected by the cranium.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The spinal cord is continuous with the brain and lies caudally to the brain.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The spinal cord reaches from the base of the skull, and continues through or starting below the foramen magnum, and terminates roughly level with the first or second lumbar vertebra, occupying the upper sections of the vertebral canal.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Microscopically, there are differences between the neurons and tissue of the CNS and the peripheral nervous system (PNS).
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The CNS is composed of white and gray matter.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] This can also be seen macroscopically on brain tissue.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The white matter consists of axons and oligodendrocytes, while the gray matter consists of neurons and unmyelinated fibers.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Both tissues include a number of glial cells (although the white matter contains more), which are often referred to as supporting cells of the CNS.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Astrocytes may be involved with both clearance of metabolites as well as transport of fuel and various beneficial substances to neurons from the capillaries of the brain.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Upon CNS injury astrocytes will proliferate, causing gliosis, a form of neuronal scar tissue, lacking in functional neurons.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The brain (cerebrum as well as midbrain and hindbrain) consists of a cortex, composed of neuron-bodies constituting gray matter, while internally there is more white matter that form tracts and commissures.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Apart from cortical gray matter there is also subcortical gray matter making up a large number of different nuclei.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] From and to the spinal cord are projections of the peripheral nervous system in the form of spinal nerves (sometimes segmental nerves).
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The nerves connect the spinal cord to skin, joints, muscles etc. and allow for the transmission of efferent motor as well as afferent sensory signals and stimuli.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] This allows for voluntary and involuntary motions of muscles, as well as the perception of senses.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] All in all 31 spinal nerves project from the brain stem, some forming plexa as they branch out, such as the brachial plexa, sacral plexa etc.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Each spinal nerve will carry both sensory and motor signals, but the nerves synapse at different regions of the spinal cord, either from the periphery to sensory relay neurons that relay the information to the CNS or from the CNS to motor neurons, which relay the information out.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The spinal cord relays information up to the brain through spinal tracts through the final common pathway to the thalamus and ultimately to the cortex.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Apart from the spinal cord, there are also peripheral nerves of the PNS that synapse through intermediaries or ganglia directly on the CNS.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] These 12 nerves exist in the head and neck region and are called cranial nerves.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Cranial nerves bring information to the CNS to and from the face, as well as to certain muscles (such as the trapezius muscle, which is innervated by accessory nerves as well as certain cervical spinal nerves).
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Two pairs of cranial nerves; the olfactory nerves and the optic nerves are often considered structures of the CNS.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] This is because they do not synapse first on peripheral ganglia, but directly on CNS neurons.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The olfactory epithelium is significant in that it consists of CNS tissue expressed in direct contact to the environment, allowing for administration of certain pharmaceuticals and drugs.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] At the anterior end of the spinal cord lies the brain.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The brain makes up the largest portion of the CNS.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] It is often the main structure referred to when speaking of the nervous system in general.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The brain is the major functional unit of the CNS.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] While the spinal cord has certain processing ability such as that of spinal locomotion and can process reflexes, the brain is the major processing unit of the nervous system.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The brainstem consists of the medulla, the pons and the midbrain.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The medulla can be referred to as an extension of the spinal cord, which both have similar organization and functional properties.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The tracts passing from the spinal cord to the brain pass through here.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Regulatory functions of the medulla nuclei include control of blood pressure and breathing.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Other nuclei are involved in balance, taste, hearing, and control of muscles of the face and neck.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The next structure rostral to the medulla is the pons, which lies on the ventral anterior side of the brainstem.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Nuclei in the pons include pontine nuclei which work with the cerebellum and transmit information between the cerebellum and the cerebral cortex.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] In the dorsal posterior pons lie nuclei that are involved in the functions of breathing, sleep, and taste.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The midbrain, or mesencephalon, is situated above and rostral to the pons.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] It includes nuclei linking distinct parts of the motor system, including the cerebellum, the basal ganglia and both cerebral hemispheres, among others.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Additionally, parts of the visual and auditory systems are located in the midbrain, including control of automatic eye movements.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The brainstem at large provides entry and exit to the brain for a number of pathways for motor and autonomic control of the face and neck through cranial nerves, Autonomic control of the organs is mediated by the tenth cranial nerve.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] A large portion of the brainstem is involved in such autonomic control of the body.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Such functions may engage the heart, blood vessels, and pupils, among others.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The brainstem also holds the reticular formation, a group of nuclei involved in both arousal and alertness.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The cerebellum is composed of several dividing fissures and lobes.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Its function includes the control of posture and the coordination of movements of parts of the body, including the eyes and head, as well as the limbs.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Further, it is involved in motion that has been learned and perfected through practice, and it will adapt to new learned movements.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Despite its previous classification as a motor structure, the cerebellum also displays connections to areas of the cerebral cortex involved in language and cognition.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] These connections have been shown by the use of medical imaging techniques, such as functional MRI and Positron emission tomography.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The body of the cerebellum holds more neurons than any other structure of the brain, including that of the larger cerebrum, but is also more extensively understood than other structures of the brain, as it includes fewer types of different neurons.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] It handles and processes sensory stimuli, motor information, as well as balance information from the vestibular organ.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The two structures of the diencephalon worth noting are the thalamus and the hypothalamus.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The thalamus acts as a linkage between incoming pathways from the peripheral nervous system as well as the optical nerve (though it does not receive input from the olfactory nerve) to the cerebral hemispheres.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Previously it was considered only a "relay station", but it is engaged in the sorting of information that will reach cerebral hemispheres (neocortex).
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Apart from its function of sorting information from the periphery, the thalamus also connects the cerebellum and basal ganglia with the cerebrum.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] In common with the aforementioned reticular system the thalamus is involved in wakefulness and consciousness, such as though the SCN.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The hypothalamus engages in functions of a number of primitive emotions or feelings such as hunger, thirst and maternal bonding.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] This is regulated partly through control of secretion of hormones from the pituitary gland.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Additionally the hypothalamus plays a role in motivation and many other behaviors of the individual.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The cerebrum of cerebral hemispheres make up the largest visual portion of the human brain.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Various structures combine to form the cerebral hemispheres, among others: the cortex, basal ganglia, amygdala and hippocampus.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The hemispheres together control a large portion of the functions of the human brain such as emotion, memory, perception and motor functions.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Apart from this the cerebral hemispheres stand for the cognitive capabilities of the brain.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Connecting each of the hemispheres is the corpus callosum as well as several additional commissures.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] One of the most important parts of the cerebral hemispheres is the cortex, made up of gray matter covering the surface of the brain.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Functionally, the cerebral cortex is involved in planning and carrying out of everyday tasks.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The hippocampus is involved in storage of memories, the amygdala plays a role in perception and communication of emotion, while the basal ganglia play a major role in the coordination of voluntary movement.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The PNS consists of neurons, axons, and Schwann cells.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Oligodendrocytes and Schwann cells have similar functions in the CNS and PNS, respectively.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Both act to add myelin sheaths to the axons, which acts as a form of insulation allowing for better and faster proliferation of electrical signals along the nerves.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Axons in the CNS are often very short, barely a few millimeters, and do not need the same degree of isolation as peripheral nerves.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Some peripheral nerves can be over 1 meter in length, such as the nerves to the big toe.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] To ensure signals move at sufficient speed, myelination is needed.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The way in which the Schwann cells and oligodendrocytes myelinate nerves differ.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] A Schwann cell usually myelinates a single axon, completely surrounding it.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Sometimes, they may myelinate many axons, especially when in areas of short axons.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Oligodendrocytes usually myelinate several axons.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] They do this by sending out thin projections of their cell membrane, which envelop and enclose the axon.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Top image: CNS as seen in a median section of a 5-week-old embryo.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Bottom image: CNS seen in a median section of a 3-month-old embryo.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] During early development of the vertebrate embryo, a longitudinal groove on the neural plate gradually deepens and the ridges on either side of the groove (the neural folds) become elevated, and ultimately meet, transforming the groove into a closed tube called the neural tube.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The formation of the neural tube is called neurulation.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] At this stage, the walls of the neural tube contain proliferating neural stem cells in a region called the ventricular zone.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The neural stem cells, principally radial glial cells, multiply and generate neurons through the process of neurogenesis, forming the rudiment of the CNS.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The neural tube gives rise to both brain and spinal cord.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The anterior (or 'rostral') portion of the neural tube initially differentiates into three brain vesicles (pockets): the prosencephalon at the front, the mesencephalon, and, between the mesencephalon and the spinal cord, the rhombencephalon.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] (By six weeks in the human embryo) the prosencephalon then divides further into the telencephalon and diencephalon; and the rhombencephalon divides into the metencephalon and myelencephalon.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The spinal cord is derived from the posterior or 'caudal' portion of the neural tube.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] As a vertebrate grows, these vesicles differentiate further still.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The telencephalon differentiates into, among other things, the striatum, the hippocampus and the neocortex, and its cavity becomes the first and second ventricles (lateral ventricles).
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Diencephalon elaborations include the subthalamus, hypothalamus, thalamus and epithalamus, and its cavity forms the third ventricle.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The tectum, pretectum, cerebral peduncle and other structures develop out of the mesencephalon, and its cavity grows into the mesencephalic duct (cerebral aqueduct).
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The metencephalon becomes, among other things, the pons and the cerebellum, the myelencephalon forms the medulla oblongata, and their cavities develop into the fourth ventricle.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] , regarded an archetypal vertebrate, lacking a true brain.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Bottom: spindle diagram of the evolution of vertebrates.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Planarians, members of the phylum Platyhelminthes (flatworms), have the simplest, clearly defined delineation of a nervous system into a CNS and a PNS.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Their primitive brains, consisting of two fused anterior ganglia, and longitudinal nerve cords form the CNS.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Like vertebrates, have a distinct CNS and PNS.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The nerves projecting laterally from the CNS form their PNS.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] A molecular study found that more than 95% of the 116 genes involved in the nervous system of planarians, which includes genes related to the CNS, also exist in humans.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] In arthropods, the ventral nerve cord, the subesophageal ganglia and the supraesophageal ganglia are usually seen as making up the CNS.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Arthropoda, unlike vertebrates, have inhibitory motor neurons due to their small size.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The CNS of chordates differs from that of other animals in being placed dorsally in the body, above the gut and notochord/spine.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The basic pattern of the CNS is highly conserved throughout the different species of vertebrates and during evolution.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The major trend that can be observed is towards a progressive telencephalisation: the telencephalon of reptiles is only an appendix to the large olfactory bulb, while in mammals it makes up most of the volume of the CNS.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] In the human brain, the telencephalon covers most of the diencephalon and the entire mesencephalon.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Indeed, the allometric study of brain size among different species shows a striking continuity from rats to whales, and allows us to complete the knowledge about the evolution of the CNS obtained through cranial endocasts.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Mammals – which appear in the fossil record after the first fishes, amphibians, and reptiles – are the only vertebrates to possess the evolutionarily recent, outermost part of the cerebral cortex (main part of the telencephalon excluding olfactory bulb) known as the neocortex.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] This part of the brain is, in mammals, involved in higher thinking and further processing of all senses in the sensory cortices (processing for smell was previously only done by its bulb while those for non-smell senses were only done by the tectum).
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The neocortex of monotremes (the duck-billed platypus and several species of spiny anteaters) and of marsupials (such as kangaroos, koalas, opossums, wombats, and Tasmanian devils) lack the convolutions – gyri and sulci – found in the neocortex of most placental mammals (eutherians).
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Within placental mammals, the size and complexity of the neocortex increased over time.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] The area of the neocortex of mice is only about 1/100 that of monkeys, and that of monkeys is only about 1/10 that of humans.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] In addition, rats lack convolutions in their neocortex (possibly also because rats are small mammals), whereas cats have a moderate degree of convolutions, and humans have quite extensive convolutions.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Extreme convolution of the neocortex is found in dolphins, possibly related to their complex echolocation.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Lastly, cancers of the central nervous system can cause severe illness and, when malignant, can have very high mortality rates.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Symptoms depend on the size, growth rate, location and malignancy of tumors and can include alterations in motor control, hearing loss, headaches and changes in cognitive ability and autonomic functioning.
[src:american-physiological-society/central-nervous-system] Specialty professional organizations recommend that neurological imaging of the brain be done only to answer a specific clinical question and not as routine screening.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The university was renamed Columbia College in 1784 following the American Revolution, and in 1787 was placed under a private board of trustees headed by former students Alexander Hamilton and John Jay.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] In 1896, the campus was moved to its current location and renamed Columbia University.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Columbia is organized into 17 schools, two affiliated colleges—Barnard College and Teachers College—and two affiliated seminaries—Jewish Theological Seminary (JTS) and Union Theological Seminary (UTS).
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The university's research efforts include the Lamont–Doherty Earth Observatory, the Goddard Institute for Space Studies, and accelerator laboratories with Big Tech firms such as Amazon and IBM.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Columbia is a founding member of the Association of American Universities and was the first school in the United States to grant the MD degree.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The university also administers and annually awards the Pulitzer Prize.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Discussions regarding the founding of a college in the Province of New York began as early as 1704.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Classes were initially held in July 1754 and were presided over by the college's first president, Samuel Johnson.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The college was officially founded on October 31, 1754, as King's College by royal charter of George II, making it the oldest institution of higher learning in the State of New York and the fifth oldest in the United States.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] In 1763, Johnson was succeeded in the presidency by Myles Cooper, a graduate of The Queen's College, Oxford, and an ardent Tory.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] In the charged political climate of the American Revolution, his chief opponent in discussions at the college was an undergraduate of the class of 1777, Alexander Hamilton.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The Irish anatomist, Samuel Clossy, was appointed professor of natural philosophy in October 1765 and later the college's first professor of anatomy in 1767.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Following the start of the American Revolutionary War and the arrival of Continental Army in 1776, the school suspended instruction for eight years.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The suspension continued through the military occupation of New York City by British troops until their departure in 1783.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] During this time, the college's library was looted and its sole building requisitioned for use as a military hospital first by American and then British forces.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The legislature agreed to assist the college.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] On May 1, 1784, it passed "an Act for granting certain privileges to the College heretofore called King's College".
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The Act created a board of regents to oversee the resuscitation of King's College.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] In April of that same year, a new charter was adopted for the college granted the power to a separate board of 24 trustees.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] For a period in the 1790s, with New York City as the federal and state capital and the country under successive Federalist governments, a revived Columbia operated under Federalists such as Hamilton and Jay.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] President George Washington and Vice President John Adams, in addition to both houses of Congress attended the college's commencement on May 6, 1789, as a tribute of honor to the alumni of the school who had been involved in the American Revolution.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] In 1813, the college incorporated its medical school with The College of Physicians and Surgeons, a new school created by the Regents of New York, forming Columbia University College of Physicians and Surgeons.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] In 1857, the college moved from the King's College campus at Park Place to a primarily Gothic Revival campus on 49th Street and Madison Avenue, where it remained for the next forty years.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] During the last half of the 19th century, under the presidency of Frederick A.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Barnard, for whom Barnard College is named, the institution rapidly assumed the shape of a modern university.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Barnard College was created in 1889 as a response to the university's refusal to accept women.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] In 1896, university president Seth Low moved the campus from 49th Street to its present location, a more spacious campus in the developing neighborhood of Morningside Heights.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] In March 1917, as a result of America's entrance into World War 1, Columbia president Nicholas Murray Butler formed the Columbia Reserve Officers Training Corps.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] All students over the age of 18 who passed a physical exam were entered into this program.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Within 4 months, over 1,400 students were enrolled within the program.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] They were one of 12 universities designated by the War department to create a naval section for the Student Army Training Corps.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] As part of this new program, the US Army charged Columbia to create a "War Issues" course.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] In 1919, a similar course was created for Columbia students, a "peace issues" course that evolved into "Introduction to Contemporary Civilization in the West", part of the university's core curriculum for undergraduate students.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] In 1919, Columbia established a student application process characterized by *The New York Times* as "the first modern college application".
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] In 1928, Seth Low Junior College was established by Columbia University in order to mitigate the number of Jewish applicants to Columbia College.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The college was closed in 1936 due to the adverse effects of the Great Depression and its students were subsequently taught at the Morningside Heights campus, although they did not belong to any college but to the university at large.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] In the 1940s, faculty members, including John R.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Dunning, Isidor Isaac Rabi, Enrico Fermi, and Polykarp Kusch, began what became the Manhattan Project, creating the first nuclear fission reactor in the Americas and researching gaseous diffusion.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] In the aftermath of World War II, the discipline of international relations became a major scholarly focus of the university, and in response, the School of International and Public Affairs was founded in 1946, drawing upon the resources of the faculties of political science, economics, and history.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] In 1947, University Extension, an evening school program open to all for a fee, was reorganized as an undergraduate college and designated the School of General Studies in response to the return of GIs after World War II.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The Columbia University Bicentennial was celebrated in 1954.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] During the 1960s, student activism reached a climax with protests in the spring of 1968, when hundreds of students occupied buildings on campus.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The incident forced the resignation of Columbia's president, Grayson Kirk, and the establishment of the University Senate.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Though several schools in the university had admitted women for years, Columbia College first admitted women in the fall of 1983, after a decade of failed negotiations with Barnard College, the all-female institution affiliated with the university, to merge the two schools.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Barnard College still remains affiliated with Columbia, and all Barnard graduates are issued diplomas signed by the presidents of Columbia University and Barnard College.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] During the late 20th century, the university underwent significant academic, structural, and administrative changes as it developed into a major research university.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] For much of the 19th century, the university consisted of decentralized and separate faculties specializing in Political Science, Philosophy, and Pure Science.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] In 1979, these faculties were merged into the Graduate School of Arts and Sciences.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] In 1995, the Division of Special Programs, later called the School of Continuing Education and now the School of Professional Studies, was established to reprise the former role of University Extension.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Bollinger became Columbia's 19th president in June 2002, succeeding George Rupp.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Bollinger was appointed in October 2001 after arriving from the presidency of the University of Michigan.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] His presidency emphasized campus expansion, defense of affirmative action in college admissions, support for government funding of private sector media, and opposition to disinformation.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Under Bollinger's tenure, the university publicly launched a record $4 billion capital campaign in September 2006.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Financial aid was improved, eliminating loans for undergraduates from families earning under $50,000, and additional funds were allocated to support Bollinger's efforts toward the Manhattanville campus expansion, which nearly doubled Columbia's physical footprint.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] This expansion was supported by a major gift from trustee Gerry Lenfest.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Globalization efforts continued with the World Leaders Forum and the creation of the Committee on Global Thought, chaired by Joseph Stiglitz.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The 2008 financial crisis impacted Columbia's endowment.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The endowment recovered, hitting $8.2B in Oct 2013.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Despite the downturn, the university pressed on with Manhattanville construction, receiving final state approval in June 2009.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] In May 2011, following the repeal of "Don't Ask, Don't Tell," the University Senate voted 51–17 to invite ROTC back after a 40-year absence, and Bollinger announced an agreement with the Navy.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Columbia has maintained its Global Centers network (Amman, Athens, Beijing, Mumbai, Paris, Nairobi, Istanbul, Santiago, Rio de Janeiro, Tunis, Tel Aviv), aiming to increase global engagement and international student enrollment.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] From 2014 to 2021, Columbia University pursued significant physical expansion, notably opening major facilities on the Manhattanville campus (ZMBBI, Lenfest Center, The Forum).
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Key strategic initiatives launched included the Knight First Amendment Institute, Columbia World Projects, and the new Columbia Climate School (2020).
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] A $5 billion university capital campaign was launched (with a $1.5B A&S target), major gifts like $50M for A&S's Uris Hall renovation were secured, and the endowment grew significantly ($14.35B by mid-2021).
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] In February 2022, Columbia's mathematics professor Michael Thaddeus published a website and argued that data submitted by Columbia for U.S.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] News college rankings was "inaccurate, dubious or highly misleading".
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] News & World Report* unranked Columbia citing failed verification.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] In September 2022, Columbia acknowledged the submission of incorrect data to U.S.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] In June 2023, Columbia announced its non-participation in the rankings.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] In July 2025, Columbia offered to pay US$9 million to settle a class-action lawsuit by its students in Manhattan federal court over the alleged submission of false data to boost its U.S.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] In January 2023, Columbia University announced that Minouche Shafik would be the school's 20th president.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Previously, Shafik served as president of the London School of Economics and Political Science.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The federal government also launched an investigation into antisemitism and then withdrew funding, prompting the university to adopt new policies and adjust disciplinary processes.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Claire Shipman was appointed acting president in March 2025.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Columbia also closed its Morningside Heights campus to the general public, allowing access only to holders of Columbia ID cards and approved guests.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] In July 2025, Columbia finalized a $220 million settlement to resume federal funding, agreeing to implement a set of reforms to address anti-semitism.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The university also adopted the IHRA definition of antisemitism.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] In January 2026, the university announced that it had chosen Jennifer Mnookin, the chancellor of the University of Wisconsin-Madison, as the next president of Columbia, effective July 1, 2026.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] In March 2026, a $481 million ruling that Columbia University had won against software company Gen Digital for infringing patents related to cybersecurity technology was overturned.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit stated that Columbia's patents may be invalid and sent the case back to Virginia federal court.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The majority of Columbia's graduate and undergraduate studies are conducted in the Upper Manhattan neighborhood of Morningside Heights on Seth Low's late-19th century vision of a university campus where all disciplines could be taught at one location.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The campus was designed along Beaux-Arts planning principles by the architects McKim, Mead & White.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Columbia's main campus occupies more than six city blocks, or 32 acres (13 ha), in Morningside Heights, New York City, a neighborhood that contains a number of academic institutions.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The university owns over 7,800 apartments in Morningside Heights, housing faculty, graduate students, and staff.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Almost two dozen undergraduate dormitories (purpose-built or converted) are located on campus or in Morningside Heights.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Columbia University has an extensive tunnel system, more than a century old, with the oldest portions predating the present campus.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Some of these remain accessible to the public, while others have been cordoned off.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Butler Library is the largest in the Columbia University Libraries system and one of the largest buildings on the campus.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] It was completed in 1934 and renamed to Butler Library in 1946.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] As of 2020, Columbia's library system includes over 15.0 million volumes, making it the eighth largest library system and fifth largest collegiate library system in the United States.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Several buildings on the Morningside Heights campus are listed on the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Low Memorial Library, a National Historic Landmark and the centerpiece of the campus, is listed for its architectural significance.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Philosophy Hall is listed as the site of the invention of FM radio.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Also listed is Pupin Hall, another National Historic Landmark, which houses the physics and astronomy departments.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Here the first experiments on the fission of uranium were conducted by Enrico Fermi.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The uranium atom was split there ten days after the world's first atom-splitting in Copenhagen, Denmark.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Other buildings listed include Casa Italiana, the Delta Psi, Alpha Chapter building of St.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Anthony Hall, Earl Hall, and the buildings of the affiliated Union Theological Seminary.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] A statue by sculptor Daniel Chester French called *Alma Mater* is centered on the front steps of Low Memorial Library.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The statue represents a personification of the traditional image of the university as an *alma mater*, or "nourishing mother", draped in an academic gown and seated on a throne.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] She wears a laurel wreath on her head and holds in her right hand a scepter capped by a King's Crown, a traditional symbol of the university.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] A book, representing learning, rests on her lap.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The arms of her throne end in lamps, representing "Sapientia et Doctrina", or "Wisdom and Learning"; on the back of the throne is embossed an image of the seal of the university.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] "The Steps", alternatively known as "Low Steps" or the "Urban Beach", are a popular meeting area for Columbia students.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The term refers to the long series of granite steps leading from the lower part of campus (South Field) to its upper terrace.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] In April 2007, the university purchased more than two-thirds of a 17 acres (6.9 ha) site for a new campus in Manhattanville, an industrial neighborhood to the north of the Morningside Heights campus.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Stretching from 125th Street to 133rd Street, Columbia Manhattanville houses buildings for Columbia's Business School, School of International and Public Affairs, Columbia School of the Arts, and the Jerome L.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Greene Center for Mind, Brain, and Behavior, where research will occur on neurodegenerative diseases such as Parkinson's and Alzheimer's.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The $7 billion expansion plan included demolishing all buildings, except three that are historically significant (the Studebaker Building, Prentis Hall, and the Nash Building), eliminating the existing light industry and storage warehouses, and relocating tenants in 132 apartments.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Replacing these buildings created 6.8 million square feet (630,000 m2) of space for the university.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Community activist groups in West Harlem fought the expansion for reasons ranging from property protection and fair exchange for land, to residents' rights.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Subsequent public hearings drew neighborhood opposition.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] As of December 2008, the State of New York's Empire State Development Corporation approved use of eminent domain, which, through declaration of Manhattanville's "blighted" status, gives governmental bodies the right to appropriate private property for public use.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] On May 20, 2009, the New York State Public Authorities Control Board approved the Manhanttanville expansion plan.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] NewYork-Presbyterian Hospital is affiliated with the medical schools of both Columbia University and Cornell University.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] News & World Report*'s "2020–21 Best Hospitals Honor Roll and Medical Specialties Rankings", it is ranked fourth overall and second among university hospitals.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Columbia's medical school has a strategic partnership with New York State Psychiatric Institute, and is affiliated with 19 other hospitals in the U.S. and four hospitals in other countries.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Health-related schools are located at the Columbia University Medical Center, a 20-acre (8.1 ha) campus located in the neighborhood of Washington Heights, fifty blocks uptown.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Other teaching hospitals affiliated with Columbia through the NewYork-Presbyterian network include the Payne Whitney Clinic in Manhattan, and the Payne Whitney Westchester, a psychiatric institute located in White Plains, New York.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] On the northern tip of Manhattan island (in the neighborhood of Inwood), Columbia owns the 26-acre (11 ha) Baker Field, which includes the Lawrence A.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Wien Stadium as well as facilities for field sports, outdoor track, and tennis.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] There is a third campus on the west bank of the Hudson River, the 157-acre (64 ha) Lamont–Doherty Earth Observatory and Earth Institute in Palisades, New York.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] A fourth is the 60-acre (24 ha) Nevis Laboratories in Irvington, New York, for the study of particle and motion physics.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] A satellite site in Paris holds classes at Reid Hall.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] In 2006, the university established the Office of Environmental Stewardship to initiate, coordinate and implement programs to reduce the university's environmental footprint.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Green Building Council selected the university's Manhattanville plan for the Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design (LEED) Neighborhood Design pilot program.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Columbia has been rated "B+" by the 2011 College Sustainability Report Card for its environmental and sustainability initiatives.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Kuchler U.S. potential natural vegetation types, Columbia University would have a dominant vegetation type of Appalachian Oak (*104*) with a dominant vegetation form of Eastern Hardwood Forest (*25*).
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Columbia Transportation is the bus service of the university, operated by Academy Bus Lines.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The buses are open to all Columbia faculty, students, Dodge Fitness Center members, and anyone else who holds a Columbia ID card.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] In addition, all TSC students can ride the buses.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] In the New York City Subway, the ("1" train) train serves the university at 116th Street-Columbia University.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The M4, M104 and M60 buses stop on Broadway while the M11 stops on Amsterdam Avenue.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The main campus is primarily boxed off by the streets of Amsterdam Avenue, Broadway, 114th street, and 120th street, with some buildings, including Barnard College, located just outside the area.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The nearest major highway is the Henry Hudson Parkway (NY 9A) to the west of the campus.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] It is located 3.4 miles (5.5 km) south of the George Washington Bridge.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Columbia is a racially diverse school, with approximately 52% of all students identifying themselves as persons of color.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Additionally, around 50% of all undergraduates received grants from Columbia.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The college is need-blind for domestic applicants.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] In April 2007, Columbia University announced a $400 million donation from media billionaire alumnus John Kluge to be used exclusively for undergraduate financial aid.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The donation is among the largest single gifts to higher education.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] However, this did not apply to international students, transfer students, visiting students, or students in the School of General Studies.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] In the fall of 2010, admission to Columbia's undergraduate colleges Columbia College and the Fu Foundation School of Engineering and Applied Science (also known as SEAS or Columbia Engineering) began accepting the Common Application.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The policy change made Columbia one of the last major academic institutions and the last Ivy League university to switch to the Common Application.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Columbia University is an independent, privately supported, nonsectarian and not-for-profit institution of higher education.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Its official corporate name is Trustees of Columbia University in the City of New York.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Joint degree programs are available through Union Theological Seminary, the Jewish Theological Seminary of America, and the Juilliard School.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Teachers College and Barnard College are official faculties of the university; both colleges' presidents are deans under the university governance structure.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The Columbia University Senate includes faculty and student representatives from Teachers College and Barnard College who serve two-year terms; all senators are accorded full voting privileges regarding matters impacting the entire university.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Teachers College is an affiliated, financially independent graduate school with their own board of trustees.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Pursuant to an affiliation agreement, Columbia is given the authority to confer "degrees and diplomas" to the graduates of Teachers College.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The degrees are signed by presidents of Teachers College and Columbia University in a manner analogous to the university's other graduate schools.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Columbia's General Studies school also has joint undergraduate programs available through University College London, Sciences Po, City University of Hong Kong, Trinity College Dublin, and the Juilliard School.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The university also has several Columbia Global Centers, in Amman, Beijing, Istanbul, Mumbai, Nairobi, Paris, Rio de Janeiro, Santiago, and Tunis.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Select students can study at either the University of Oxford or the University of Cambridge for a year if approved by both Columbia and either Oxford or Cambridge.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Columbia also has a dual MA program with the Aga Khan University in London.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Columbia University was ranked 12th in the United States and tenth globally for 2023–2024 by *U.S.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] In 2021, Columbia was ranked seventh in the world (sixth in the United States) by *Academic Ranking of World Universities*, sixth in the world by *U.S.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] News & World Report*, 19th in the world by *QS World University Rankings*, and 11th globally by *Times Higher Education World University Rankings*.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] It was ranked in the first tier of American research universities, along with Harvard, MIT, and Stanford, in the 2019 report from the Center for Measuring University Performance.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] In 2025, Columbia was ranked 250 out of 257 top colleges in "Free Speech Rankings" by the Foundation for Individual Rights and Expression and "College Pulse", after ranking 214 of 248 in 2024 and at the bottom of 203 in 2022/2023.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] In 2024 and 2025, Columbia received a D on the "Campus Antisemitism Report Card" of the Anti-Defamation League, which the advocacy organization first launched in spring 2024, in the lead-up to and in the context of campus conflict over the 2024 Columbia University pro-Palestinian campus occupations.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Columbia University has been the site of many scientific milestones, including the first nuclear fission in North America, the invention of FM radio and the laser, and key contributions to neuroscience.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Researchers at Columbia have also advanced efforts in technology, such as digital media, cellular imaging, and brain-computer interfaces.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Columbia is classified among "R1: Doctoral Universities – Very high research activity".
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Columbia scientists have been credited with about 175 new inventions in the health sciences each year.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Columbia is affiliated with many research facilities, such as the Columbia Institute for Tele-Information dedicated to telecommunications and the Goddard Institute for Space Studies, which is an astronomical observatory affiliated with NASA.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Columbia is a long-standing participant of the United States Department of Veterans Affairs Yellow Ribbon Program, allowing eligible veterans and their dependents to pursue a Columbia undergraduate degree regardless of socioeconomic status for over 70 years.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Several prestigious awards are administered by Columbia University, most notably the Pulitzer Prize and the Bancroft Prize in history.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Other prizes, which are awarded by the Graduate School of Journalism, include the Alfred I. duPont–Columbia University Award, the National Magazine Awards, the Maria Moors Cabot Prizes, the John Chancellor Award, and the Lukas Prizes, which include the J.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Anthony Lukas Book Prize and Mark Lynton History Prize.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The university also administers the Louisa Gross Horwitz Prize, which is considered an important precursor to the Nobel Prize, 55 of its 117 recipients having gone on to win either a Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine or Nobel Prize in Chemistry as of October 2024; the W.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Alden Spencer Award; the Vetlesen Prize, which is known as the Nobel Prize of geology; the Japan-U.S.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Friendship Commission Prize for the Translation of Japanese Literature, the oldest such award; the Edwin Howard Armstrong award; the Calderone Prize in public health; and the Ditson Conductor's Award.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] In 2020, Columbia University's student population was 31,455 (8,842 students in undergraduate programs and 22,613 in postgraduate programs), with 45% of the student population identifying themselves as a minority.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Twenty-six percent of students at Columbia have family incomes below $60,000.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] 16% of students at Columbia receive Federal Pell Grants, which mostly go to students whose family incomes are below $40,000.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Seventeen percent of students are the first member of their family to attend a four-year college.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Columbia University is home to many fraternities, sororities, and co-educational Greek organizations.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Approximately 10–15% of undergraduate students are associated with Greek life.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Many Barnard women also join Columbia sororities.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] There has been a Greek presence on campus since the establishment in 1836 of the Delta chapter of Alpha Delta Phi.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The *Columbia Daily Spectator* is the nation's second-oldest continuously operating daily student newspaper.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] *The Blue and White* is a monthly literary magazine established in 1890 that discusses campus life and local politics.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] *Bwog*, originally an offshoot of *The Blue and White* but now fully independent, is an online campus news and entertainment source.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] *The Morningside Post* is a student-run multimedia news publication.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Columbia is home to numerous undergraduate academic publications.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The *Columbia Undergraduate Science Journal* prints original science research in its two annual publications.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Other publications include *The Columbian*, the undergraduate colleges' annually published yearbook; the *Gadfly*, a biannual journal of popular philosophy produced by undergraduates; and *Rhapsody in Blue*, an undergraduate urban studies magazine.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Professional journals published by academic departments include *Current Musicology* and *The Journal of Philosophy*.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The Graduate School of Journalism publishe*s The Bronx Beat* each spring, a bi-weekly newspaper covering the South Bronx.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] In 1961, the journalism school founded the *Columbia Journalism Review*, a professional magazine which is published six times a year.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Defunct publications include the *Columbia University Forum*, a review of literature and cultural affairs for alumni.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Columbia is home to two pioneers in undergraduate campus radio broadcasting, WKCR-FM and CTV.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] A student-run radio station, WKCR broadcasts to the Tri-state area and claims to be the oldest FM radio station in the world, owing to the university's affiliation with Edwin Howard Armstrong.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The station has its studios on the second floor of Alfred Lerner Hall on the Morningside campus with its main transmitter tower at 4 Times Square in Midtown Manhattan.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Columbia Television (CTV) is the nation's second oldest student television station and the home of CTV News, a weekly live news program produced by undergraduate students.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The Philolexian Society is a literary and debating club founded in 1802, making it the oldest student group at Columbia, as well as the third oldest collegiate literary society in the country.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The society annually administers the Joyce Kilmer Memorial Bad Poetry Contest.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The Columbia Parliamentary Debate Team competes in tournaments around the country as part of the American Parliamentary Debate Association, and hosts both high school and college tournaments on Columbia's campus, as well as public debates on issues affecting the university.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The Columbia International Relations Council and Association (CIRCA), oversees Columbia's Model United Nations activities.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] CIRCA hosts college and high school Model UN conferences, hosts speakers influential in international politics to speak on campus, and trains students from underprivileged schools in New York in Model UN.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Many engineering entrepreneurs in New York City have attended Columbia.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Since 1990, graduates of Columbia have established more than 100 technology companies.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The student-run group Columbia University Organization of Rising Entrepreneurs (CORE) was founded in 1999 with an aim to foster entrepreneurship on campus.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Each year CORE hosts events, including #StartupColumbia, a conference and venture competition for $250,000, and Ignite@CU, a weekend for undergrads interested in design, engineering, and entrepreneurship.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Notable speakers include Peter Thiel, Jack Dorsey, Alexis Ohanian, Drew Houston, and Mark Cuban.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] CampusNetwork, an on-campus social networking site called Campus Network that preceded Facebook, was created and popularized by Columbia engineering student Adam Goldberg in 2003.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Mark Zuckerberg later asked Goldberg to join him in Palo Alto to work on Facebook, but Goldberg declined the offer.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The Fu Foundation School of Engineering and Applied Science offers a minor in Technical Entrepreneurship through its Center for Technology, Innovation, and Community Engagement.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] SEAS' entrepreneurship activities focus on community building initiatives in New York and worldwide, made possible through partners such as Microsoft Corporation.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Bloomberg launched the NYC Media Lab to promote innovations in New York's media industry.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Situated at the New York University Tandon School of Engineering, the lab is a consortium of Columbia University, New York University, and New York City Economic Development Corporation acting to connect companies with universities in new technology research.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The Lab is modeled after similar ones at MIT and Stanford, and was established with a $250,000 grant from the New York City Economic Development Corporation.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Established in 2003 by university president Lee C.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Bollinger, the World Leaders Forum at Columbia University provides the opportunity for students and faculty to listen to world leaders in government, religion, industry, finance, and academia.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Other speakers include President Yudhoyono of Indonesia, President Pervez Musharraf of the Islamic Republic of Pakistan, Iraq President Jalal Talabani, the 14th Dalai Lama, president of the Islamic Republic of Iran Mahmoud Ahmadinejad, financier George Soros, Mayor of New York City Michael R.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Bloomberg, President Václav Klaus of the Czech Republic, President Cristina Fernández de Kirchner of Argentina, former Secretary-General of the United Nations Kofi Annan, and Al Gore.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The Columbia University Orchestra was founded by composer Edward MacDowell in 1896, and is the oldest continually operating university orchestra in the United States.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Undergraduate student composers at Columbia may choose to become involved with Columbia New Music, which sponsors concerts of music written by undergraduate students from all of Columbia's schools.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The Notes and Keys, the oldest a cappella group at Columbia, was founded in 1909.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The Columbia Queer Alliance is the central Columbia student organization that represents the bisexual, lesbian, gay, transgender, and questioning student population.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] It is the oldest gay student organization in the world, founded as the Student Homophile League in 1967 by students including lifelong activist Stephen Donaldson.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Columbia University campus military groups include the U.S.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Military Veterans of Columbia University and Advocates for Columbia ROTC.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] In the 2005–06 academic year, the Columbia Military Society, Columbia's student group for ROTC cadets and Marine officer candidates, was renamed the Hamilton Society for "students who aspire to serve their nation through the military in the tradition of Alexander Hamilton".
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Columbia has several secret societies, including St.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Anthony Hall, which was founded at the university in 1847, and two senior societies, the Nacoms and Sachems.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] A member institution of the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) in Division I FCS, Columbia fields varsity teams in 29 sports and is a member of the Ivy League.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The football Lions play home games at the 17,000-seat Robert K.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The Baker Athletics Complex also includes facilities for baseball, softball, soccer, lacrosse, field hockey, tennis, track, and rowing, as well as the new Campbell Sports Center, which opened in January 2013.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The basketball, fencing, swimming & diving, volleyball, and wrestling programs are based at the Dodge Physical Fitness Center on the main campus.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Former students include Baseball Hall of Famers Lou Gehrig and Eddie Collins, football Hall of Famer Sid Luckman, Marcellus Wiley, and world champion women's weightlifter Karyn Marshall.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] On May 17, 1939, fledgling NBC broadcast a doubleheader between the Columbia Lions and the Princeton Tigers at Columbia's Baker Field, making it the first televised regular athletic event in history.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Columbia University participated in multiple firsts within collegiate athletics.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The football program is best known for its record of futility set during the 1980s: between 1983 and 1988, the team lost 44 games in a row, which is still the record for the NCAA Football Championship Subdivision.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The streak was broken on October 8, 1988, with a 16–13 victory over arch-rival Princeton University.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] That was the Lions' first victory at Wien Stadium, which had been opened during the losing streak and was already four years old.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] A new tradition has developed with the Liberty Cup.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The Liberty Cup is awarded annually to the winner of the football game between Fordham and Columbia Universities, two of the only three NCAA Division I football teams in New York City.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The Varsity Show is one of the oldest traditions at Columbia.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Founded in 1893 as a fundraiser for the university's fledgling athletic teams, the Varsity Show now draws together the entire Columbia undergraduate community for a series of performances every April.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Dedicated to producing a unique full-length musical that skewers and satirizes many dubious aspects of life at Columbia, the Varsity Show is written and performed exclusively by university undergraduates.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Various renowned playwrights, composers, authors, directors, and actors have contributed to the Varsity Show, either as writers or performers, while students at Columbia, including Richard Rodgers, Oscar Hammerstein II, Lorenz Hart, Herman J.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Diamond, Herman Wouk, Greta Gerwig, and Kate McKinnon.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Notable past shows include *Fly With Me* (1920), *The* *Streets of New York* (1948), *The Sky's the Limit* (1954), and *Angels at Columbia* (1994).
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] In particular, *Streets of New York*, after having been revived three times, opened off-Broadway in 1963 and was awarded a 1964 Drama Desk Award.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] *The Mischief Maker* (1903), written by Edgar Allan Woolf and Cassius Freeborn, premiered at Madison Square Garden in 1906 as *Mam'zelle Champagne*.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The campus Tree Lighting ceremony was inaugurated in 1998.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] It celebrates the illumination of the medium-sized trees lining College Walk in front of Kent Hall and Hamilton Hall on the east end and Dodge Hall and Pulitzer Hall on the west, just before finals week in early December.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Students meet at the sundial for free hot chocolate, performances by *a cappella* groups, and speeches by the university president and a guest.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Immediately following the College Walk festivities is one of Columbia's older holiday traditions, the lighting of the Yule Log.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The Christmas ceremony dates to a period prior to the American Revolutionary War, but lapsed before being revived by President Nicholas Murray Butler in 1910.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] A troop of students dressed as Continental Army soldiers carry the eponymous log from the sundial to the lounge of John Jay Hall, where it is lit amid the singing of seasonal carols.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] The Christmas ceremony is accompanied by a reading of *A Visit From St.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p01] Nicholas* by Clement Clarke Moore and *Yes, Virginia, There is a Santa Claus* by Francis Pharcellus Church.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] The university has graduated many notable alumni, including five Founding Fathers of the United States, an author of the United States Constitution and a member of the Committee of Five.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] Three United States presidents have attended Columbia, as well as ten justices of the Supreme Court of the United States, including three chief justices.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] As of 2011, 125 Pulitzer Prize winners and 39 Oscar winners have attended Columbia.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] Columbia faculty received multiple Nobel Prizes, including Joseph Stiglitz (Economics, 2001), Richard Axel and Linda Buck (Medicine, 2004), Edmund Phelps (Economics, 2006), and Orhan Pamuk (Literature, 2006), among others.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] In a 2016 ranking of universities worldwide with respect to living graduates who are billionaires, Columbia ranked second, after Harvard.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] Presidents Theodore Roosevelt and Franklin Delano Roosevelt attended the law school.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] Other political figures educated at Columbia include former U.S.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] President Barack Obama, Associate Justice of the U.S.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] Supreme Court Ruth Bader Ginsburg,, William O.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] Douglas, Supreme Court Justice and former Chairman of the Securities and Exchange Commission, former U.S.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, former chairman of the U.S.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] Federal Reserve Bank Alan Greenspan, U.S.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] One of the founding fathers of modern India and the prime architect of the Constitution of India, B.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] Alumni of Columbia have occupied top positions in Wall Street and the rest of the business world.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] Notable members of the Astor family attended Columbia, while other business graduates include investor Warren Buffett, former CEO of PBS and NBC Lawrence K.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] Robson Walton, Bain Capital Co-Managing Partner, Jonathan Lavine, Thomson Reuters CEO Tom Glocer, New York Stock Exchange president Lynn Martin, and AllianceBernstein Chairman and CEO Lewis A.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] CEOs of top Fortune 500 companies include James P.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] Stevens of Lockheed Martin, Philippe Dauman of Viacom, Robert Bakish of Paramount Global, Ursula Burns of Xerox, Devin Wenig of EBay, Vikram Pandit of Citigroup, Ralph Izzo of Public Service Enterprise Group, Gail Koziara Boudreaux of Anthem, and Frank Blake of The Home Depot.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] Labor organizer and women's educator Louise Leonard McLaren received her degree of Master of Arts from Columbia.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] Many Columbia alumni have gone on to renowned careers in the arts, including composers Richard Rodgers, Oscar Hammerstein II, Lorenz Hart, and Art Garfunkel; and painter Georgia O'Keeffe.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] Five United States Poet Laureates received their degrees from Columbia.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] Columbia alumni have made an indelible mark in the field of American poetry and literature, with such people as Jack Kerouac and Allen Ginsberg, pioneers of the Beat Generation; and Langston Hughes and Zora Neale Hurston, seminal figures in the Harlem Renaissance, all having attended the university.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] Other notable writers who attended Columbia include authors Isaac Asimov, J.D.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] Le Guin, Danielle Valore Evans, and Hunter S.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] In architecture, William Lee Stoddart, a prolific architect of U.S.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] University alumni have also been very prominent in the film industry, with 33 alumni and former students winning a combined 43 Academy Awards (as of 2011).
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] Some notable Columbia alumni that have gone on to work in film include directors Sidney Lumet (*12 Angry Men*) and Kathryn Bigelow (*The Hurt Locker*), screenwriters Howard Koch (*Casablanca*) and Joseph L.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] Mankiewicz (*All About Eve*), and actors James Cagney, Ed Harris and Timothée Chalamet.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] Columbia University's faculty has included many notable names in the role of university president, including 34th President of the United States Dwight D.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] Eisenhower, 4th Vice President of the United States George Clinton, Founding Father and U.S.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] Senator from Connecticut William Samuel Johnson, Nobel Peace Prize laureate Nicholas Murray Butler, and First Amendment scholar Lee Bollinger.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] Other notable Columbia University faculty include Zbigniew Brzezinski, Sonia Sotomayor, Kimberlé Crenshaw, Lee Bollinger, Franz Boas, Margaret Mead, Edward Sapir, John Dewey, Charles A.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] As of 2021, Columbia employs 4,381 faculty, including 70 members of the National Academy of Sciences, 178 members of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences, and 65 members of the National Academy of Medicine.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] In total, the Columbia faculty has included 52 Nobel laureates, 12 National Medal of Science recipients, and 32 National Academy of Engineering members.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] Columbia University faculty played particularly important roles during World War II and the creation of the New Deal under President Franklin D.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] Roosevelt, who attended Columbia Law School.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] The three core members of Roosevelt's Brain Trust: Adolf A.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] Berle, Raymond Moley, and Rexford Tugwell, were law professors at Columbia.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] Former United States Secretary of Labor, Francis Perkins was the principle architect of the New Deal and also earned her Master's from Columbia University.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] The Statistical Research Group, which used statistics to analyze military problems during World War II, was composed of Columbia researchers and faculty including George Stigler and Milton Friedman.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] Columbia faculty and researchers, including Enrico Fermi, Leo Szilard, Eugene T.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] Pegram, Walter Zinn, Chien-Shiung Wu, Francis G.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] Anderson, and Isidor Isaac Rabi, also played a significant role during the early phases of the Manhattan Project.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] Following the rise of Nazi Germany, the exiled Institute for Social Research at Goethe University Frankfurt would affiliate itself with Columbia from 1934 to 1950.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] It was during this period that thinkers including Theodor W.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] Adorno, Max Horkheimer, and Herbert Marcuse wrote and published some of the most seminal works of the Frankfurt School, including *Reason and Revolution*, *Dialectic of Enlightenment*, and *Eclipse of Reason*.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] Professors Edward Said, author of *Orientalism*, and Gayatri Chakravorty Spivak are generally considered as founders of the field of postcolonialism; other professors that have significantly contributed to the field include Hamid Dabashi, Rashid Khalidi, and Joseph Massad.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] The works of professors Kimberlé Crenshaw, Patricia J.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] Williams, and Kendall Thomas were foundational to the field of critical race theory.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] Columbia and its affiliated faculty have also made significant contributions to the study of religion.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] The affiliated Union Theological Seminary is a center of liberal Christianity in the United States, having served as the birthplace of Black theology through the efforts of faculty including James H.
[src:american-physiological-society/columbia-university-p02] Cone and Cornel West, and Womanist theology, through the works of Katie Cannon, Emilie Townes, and Delores S.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] A **committee** or **commission** is a body of one or more persons subordinate to a deliberative assembly or other form of organization.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] A committee may not itself be considered to be a form of assembly or a decision-making body.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] Usually, an assembly or organization sends matters to a committee as a way to explore them more fully than would be possible if the whole assembly or organization were considering them.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] Committees may have different functions and their types of work differ depending on the type of organization and its needs.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] A member of a legislature may be delegated a **committee assignment**, which gives them the right to serve on a certain committee.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] A deliberative assembly or other organization may form a committee (or "commission") consisting of one or more persons to assist with the work of the assembly.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] For larger organizations, much work is done in committees.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] They can be a way to formally draw together people of relevant expertise from different parts of an organization who otherwise would not have a good way to share information and coordinate actions.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] They may have the advantage of widening viewpoints and sharing out responsibilities.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] They can also be appointed with experts to recommend actions in matters that require specialized knowledge or technical judgment.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] In organizations considered too large for all the members to participate in decisions affecting the organization as a whole, a smaller body, such as a board of directors, is given the power to make decisions, spend money, or take actions.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] is formed as a separate committee to review the performance of the board and board policy as well as nominate candidates for the board.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] A large body may have smaller committees with more specialized functions.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] Examples are an audit committee, an elections committee, a finance committee, a fundraising committee, and a program committee.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] are usually organized by a coordinating committee drawn from the membership of the organization.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] Committees may be formed to do research and make recommendations on a potential or planned project or change.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] might create a temporary working committee of several people to review options and make recommendations to upper management or the board of directors.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] A committee on discipline may be used to handle disciplinary procedures for members of the organization.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] by sending sensitive, inconvenient, or irrelevant matters to committees, organizations may bypass, stall, or disacknowledge matters without declaring a formal policy of inaction or indifference.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] Generally, committees are required to report to their parent body.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] They do not usually have the power to act independently unless the body that created it gives it such power.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] Electoral accountability can affect committee activity.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] When a committee is formed in a formal situation, such as committees in legislatures or for corporate bodies with by-laws, a chairman (or "chair" or "chairperson") is designated for the committee.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] Sometimes a vice-chairman (or similar name) is also appointed.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] It is common for the committee chairman to organize its meetings.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] Sometimes these meetings are held through videoconferencing or other means if committee members are not able to attend in person, as may be the case if they are in different parts of the country or the world.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] The chairman is responsible for running meetings.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] Duties include keeping the discussion on the appropriate subject, recognizing members to speak, and confirming what the committee has decided (through voting or by unanimous consent).
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] Using *Robert's Rules of Order Newly Revised* (RONR), committees may follow informal procedures (such as not requiring motions if it is clear what is being discussed).
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] The level of formality depends on the size and type of committee, in which sometimes larger committees considering crucial issues may require more formal processes.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] Minutes are a record of the decisions at meetings.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] They can be taken by a person designated as the secretary.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] For most organizations, committees are not required to keep formal minutes.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] However, some bodies require that committees take minutes, especially if the committees are public ones subject to open meeting laws.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] Committees may meet on a regular basis, such as weekly or more often, or meetings may be called irregularly as the need arises.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] The frequency of the meetings depends on the work of the committee and the needs of the parent body.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] When the committee completes its work, it provides the results in a report to its parent body.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] The report may include the methods used, the facts uncovered, the conclusions reached, and any recommendations.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] If the committee is not ready to report, it may provide a partial report or the assembly may discharge the committee of the matter so that the assembly can handle it.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] Also, if members of the committee are not performing their duties, they may be removed or replaced by the appointing power.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] Whether the committee continues to exist after presenting its report depends on the type of committee.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] Generally, committees established by the bylaws or the organization's rules continue to exist, while committees formed for a particular purpose go out of existence after the final report.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] In parliamentary procedure, the motion to **commit** (or **refer**) is used to refer another motion—usually a main motion—to a committee.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] Any proposed amendments to the main motion that are pending at the time the motion is referred to a committee go to the committee as well.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] Once referred, but before the committee reports its recommendations back to the assembly, the referred motion may be removed from the committee's consideration by the motion to discharge a committee.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] In the United States House of Representatives, a motion to recommit can be made with or without instructions.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] If the motion is made without instructions, the bill or resolution is simply sent back to the committee.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] If the motion is made with instructions and the motion is agreed to, the chairman of the committee in question will immediately report the bill or resolution back to the whole House with the new language.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] In this sense, a motion to recommit with instructions is effectively an amendment.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] In *Robert's Rules of Order Newly Revised* (*RONR*), the motion to commit has three variations which do not turn a question over to a smaller group, but simply permit the assembly's full meeting body to consider it with the greater freedom of debate that is allowed to committees.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] These forms are to go into a committee of the whole, to go into a quasi-committee of the whole, and to consider informally.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] Passing any of these motions removes the limitations on the number of times a member can speak.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] *The Standard Code of Parliamentary Procedure* has informal consideration, but does not have "committee of the whole" or "quasi committee of the whole".
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] In *Robert's Rules of Order Newly Revised*, the motion to discharge a committee is used to take a matter out of a committee's hands before the committee has made a final report on it.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] A committee can use this motion to discharge a subcommittee.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] The vote required is a majority vote, if the committee has failed to report at the prescribed time or if the assembly is considering a partial report of the committee.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] Otherwise, it requires a majority vote with previous notice; a two-thirds vote; or a majority of the entire membership.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] Under *The Standard Code of Parliamentary Procedure*, the assembly that has referred a motion or a matter to a committee may, by a majority vote, withdraw it at any time from the committee, refer it to another committee, or decide the question itself.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] Organizations with a large board of directors (such as international labor unions, large corporations with thousands of stockholders or national and international organizations) may have a smaller body of the board, called an *executive committee*, to handle its business.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] The executive committee may function more like a board than an actual committee.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] In any case, an executive committee can only be established through a specific provision in the charter or bylaws of the entity (i.e. a board cannot appoint an executive committee without authorization to do so).
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] Members of the executive committee may be elected by the overall franchised membership or by the board, depending on the rules of the organization, and usually consist of the CEO and the Vice Presidents in charge of respective directorates within the organization.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] However formed, an executive committee only has such powers and authority that the governing documents of the organization give it.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] In some cases, it may be empowered to act on behalf of the board or organization, while in others, it may only be able to make recommendations.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] Governments at the national level may have a *conference committee*.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] A conference committee in a bicameral legislature is responsible for creating a compromise version of a particular bill when each house has passed a different version.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] A conference committee in the United States Congress is a temporary panel of negotiators from the House of Representatives and the Senate.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] Unless one chamber decides to accept the other's original bill, the compromise version must pass both chambers after leaving the conference committee.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] This committee is usually composed of the senior members of the standing committees that originally considered the legislation in each chamber.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] Other countries that use conference committees include France, Germany, Japan, and Switzerland.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] In Canada, conference committees have been unused since 1947.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] In the European Union (EU) legislative process, a similar committee is called a 'Conciliation Committee', which carries out the Trilogue negotiations in case the Council does not agree with a text amended and adopted by the European Parliament at a second reading.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] Although the practice has fallen out of favour in other Australian Parliaments, the Parliament of South Australia still regularly appoints a "Conference of Managers" from each House to negotiate compromises on disputed bills in private.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] In organizations, the term "conference committee" may have a different meaning.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] This meaning may be associated with the conferences, or conventions, that the organization puts together.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] These committees that are responsible for organizing such events may be called "conference committees".
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] A **standing committee** is a subunit of a political or deliberative body established in a permanent fashion to aid the parent assembly in accomplishing its duties, for example by meeting on a specific, permanent policy domain (e.g. defence, health, or trade and industry).
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] A standing committee is granted its scope and powers over a particular area of business by the governing documents.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] Standing committees meet on a regular or irregular basis depending on their function, and retain any power or oversight originally given them until subsequent official actions of the governing body (through changes to law or by-laws) disbands the committee.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] Most governmental legislative committees are standing committees.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] Under the laws of the United States of America, a standing committee is a Congressional committee permanently authorized by the United States House of Representatives and United States Senate rules.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] The Legislative Reorganization Act of 1946 greatly reduced the number of committees, and set up the legislative committee structure still in use today, as modified by authorized changes via the orderly mechanism of rule changes.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] Examples of standing committees in organizations are; an audit committee, an elections committee, a finance committee, a fundraising committee, a governance committee, and a program committee.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] Typically, the standing committees perform their work throughout the year and present their reports at the annual meeting of the organization.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] These committees continue to exist after presenting their reports, although the membership in the committees may change.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] A **nominating committee** (or nominations committee) is a group formed for the purpose of nominating candidates for office or the board in an organization.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] It may consist of members from inside the organization.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] Sometimes a governance committee takes the role of a nominating committee.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] Depending on the organization, this committee may be empowered to actively seek out candidates or may only have the power to receive nominations from members and verify that the candidates are eligible.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] A nominating committee works similarly to an electoral college, the main difference being that the available candidates, either nominated or "written in" outside of the committee's choices, are then voted into office by the membership.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] It is a part of governance methods often employed by corporate bodies, business entities, and social and sporting groups, especially clubs.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] The intention is that they be made up of qualified and knowledgeable people representing the best interests of the membership.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] In the case of business entities, their directors will often be brought in from outside, and receive a benefit for their expertise.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] The objective being to update, set, and maintain high and possibly new standards.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] A **steering committee** is a committee that provides guidance, direction and control to a project within an organization.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] The term is derived from the steering mechanism that changes the steering angle of a vehicle's wheels.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] Project steering committees are frequently used for guiding and monitoring IT projects in large organizations, as part of project governance.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] The functions of the committee might include building a business case for the project, planning, providing assistance and guidance, monitoring the progress, controlling the project scope and resolving conflicts.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] As with other committees, the specific duties and role of the steering committee vary among organizations.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] A coalition committee is a steering committee for a coalition government, an informal body composed of leading figures from the coalition parties and the government.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] Coalition committees, in contrast to parliamentary committees, have no formal rights.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] A **special committee** (also working, select, or ad hoc committee) is established to accomplish a particular task or to oversee a specific area in need of control or oversight.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] Many are research or coordination committees in type or purpose and are temporary.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] Some are a sub-group of a larger society with a particular area of interest which are organized to meet and discuss matters pertaining to their interests.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] For example; a group of astronomers might be organized to discuss how to get the larger society to address near Earth objects.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] A subgroup of engineers and scientists of a large project's development team could be organized to solve some particular issue with offsetting considerations and trade-offs.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] Once the committee makes its final report to its parent body, the special committee ceases to exist.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] A committee that is a subset of a larger committee is called a *subcommittee*.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] Committees that have a large workload may form subcommittees to further divide the work.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] Subcommittees report to the parent committee and not to the general assembly.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] When the entire assembly meets as a committee to discuss or debate, this is called a "committee of the whole".
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] This is a procedural device most commonly used by legislative bodies to discuss an issue under the rules of a committee meeting rather than the more formal and rigid rules which would have to be followed to actually enact legislation.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] "Central Committee" is the common designation of the highest organ of communist parties between congresses.
[src:american-physiological-society/committee] It is elected by the party congress, directs party activities, and elects the politburo and the general secretary.
